# Calculatting and filtering the data with Quantity

IQR_Totalsales <- IQR(Retaildataupdated$Totalsales, na.rm = TRUE)
Q1_Totalsales <- quantile(Retaildataupdated$Totalsales, 0.25, na.rm = TRUE)
Q3_Totalsales <- quantile(Retaildataupdated$Totalsales, 0.75, na.rm = TRUE)


lower_bound_Totalsales <- Q1_Totalsales - 3 * IQR_Totalsales
upper_bound_Totalsales <- Q3_Totalsales + 3 * IQR_Totalsales

Retaildatafiltered <- Retaildataupdated[Retaildataupdated$Totalsales >= lower_bound_Totalsales & Retaildataupdated$Totalsales <= upper_bound_Totalsales,]
library(dplyr)

Retaildatafiltered <- Retaildatafiltered %>% filter(UnitPrice >= 0.01)

Removed all observations under UnitPrice who’s value is less than or equal to 0.01 as the data is missing the prices for these records and needs to be omitted for a clean dataset.

getSeason <- function(date) {
  month <- as.numeric(format(date, "%m"))
  if (month %in% 3:5) {
    return("Spring")
  } else if (month %in% 6:8) {
    return("Summer")
  } else if (month %in% 9:11) {
    return("Fall")
  } else {
    return("Winter")
  }
}

# Apply the function to create a new 'Season' column
Retaildatafiltered$Season <- sapply(Retaildatafiltered$InvoiceDate, getSeason)

library(lubridate)

Retaildatafiltered$DayOfWeek <- wday(Retaildatafiltered$InvoiceDate, label = TRUE, abbr = FALSE)

# Now aggregate sales by the day of the week
sales_pattern <- Retaildatafiltered %>%
  group_by(DayOfWeek) %>%
  summarize(Totalsales = sum(Totalsales, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  mutate(DayOfWeek = factor(DayOfWeek, levels = c("Sunday", "Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday")))

ggplot(sales_pattern, aes(x = DayOfWeek, y = Totalsales, fill = DayOfWeek)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(title = "Sales Pattern per Day of the Week", x = "Day of the Week", y = "Total Sales") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

The above bar chart shows the total sales for each day of the week. The height of each bar represent the total sales values which are colored visually. From this barchart, we can conclude that Tuesday appears to have the highest sales, which is followed by Monday and Sunday claiming second and third position. Thursday is the lowest among the weekdays. And this pattern interpreting that the beginning of the week is the strongest period for sales, with a dip in the middle of the week, and again picking up during the weekends.

UnitPrice Quantity Totalsales

Totalsales 0.2910981 0.4241169 1.0000000

UnitPrice-Quantity: The correlation coefficient between the unit price of the items and the quantity sold is roughly -0.2748, suggesting a weakly negative linear relationship. The quantity sold typically declines slightly as the unit price rises, or vice versa. UnitPrice-Total Sales: There appears to be a slight positive linear relationship, as indicated by the correlation coefficient of roughly 0.2911. This could suggest that higher-priced items contribute more to the total sales value despite possibly lower quantities sold. It also means that as the unit price increases, the total sales value also tends to increase slightly. Quantity-Total-Sales: A moderately positive linear relationship is indicated by the correlation coefficient, which is roughly 0.4241. This makes sense because selling more things would normally result in a higher total sales value as the number of items sold rises.

The other dummy variable we have created is InvoiceDummy, which is a binary variable, containing values of 0 and 1, where 0 represents the InvoiceIds that start with C, which means cancelled orders and 1 represents succesful orders. We created this variable to find out the percentage or proportion of returns/cancellations from the whole population of orders.

#### The first bin contains the majority of the unit prices, suggesting that low-priced items are found there frequently. # Let's set analysis date as one day after the last invoice date in the Retail dataset
retail_analysis_date <- max(Retail_sales$InvoiceDate) + days(1)

rfm_table <- Retail_sales %>%
             group_by(CustomerID) %>%
             summarize(Recency = as.numeric(retail_analysis_date - max(InvoiceDate)),
                       Frequency = n_distinct(InvoiceNo),
                       Monetary = sum(Totalsales))

rfm_table <- rfm_table %>%
             mutate(R_Score = ntile(-Recency, 5),
                    F_Score = ntile(Frequency, 5),
                    M_Score = ntile(Monetary, 5))


rfm_table <- rfm_table %>%
             mutate(RFM_Score = R_Score + F_Score + M_Score)
library(knitr)

#### Top 10 Customers by Monetary Value - When displaying data in descending order, this kind of chart is frequently used to quickly identify the top items—in this case, the top customers based on the dollar amount of their purchases. Customer IDs, or unique customer identifiers, are listed on the y-axis. These IDs are numbers, such as 14096, 14298, 14911, and so on. The Monetary Value, shown on the x-axis, is most likely the total amount spent or revenue contributed by each customer. The monetary value range is indicated by the scale, which appears to go from 0 to more than 40,000. The length of each bar represents the total monetary value assigned to that particular customer; the customer with the highest monetary value is represented by the longest bar at the top, and those with lower monetary values are represented by shorter bars. The remaining customers are arranged in order of highest to lowest value. Of the top 10, Customer 12921 has the lowest monetary value, but it is still significant enough to be displayed in this chart. A company could use this chart to determine which of its clients are the most valuable, and then use that information to target retention campaigns, customized marketing campaigns, or other customer engagement initiatives. It also exemplifies the Pareto 80/20 rule, which is applicable in many business contexts and states that a small percentage of revenue may come from a small number of customers.

The intercept is 2.0475, which indicates that the expected value of Log_Quantity is approximately 2.048 if all other variables are zero. This is statistically very significant. With positive coefficients of 0.0864 and 0.1178, respectively, SeasonSpring and SeasonSummer are linked to higher Log_Quantity values than the baseline season— Autumn and are both highly significant.The data for SeasonWinter indicates a small negative coefficient (-0.0045) but no statistically significant difference in Log_Quantity between Winter and the baseline (p-value 0.632). The significant negative coefficient (-0.6267) of GroupedCountryUK indicates that residing in the UK is linked to a decline in Log_Quantity. The actual values generally differ by this amount from the predicted values, as indicated by the residual standard error of 1.076. With an R-squared of 0.03292, the model can only account for roughly 3.29% of the variability in Log_Quantity. Given the low value, it is possible that the model does not account for other significant variables.

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(regressmodel2)

#### A linear regression model’s diagnostic plots, shown above, are intended to evaluate the soundness of the model’s underlying assumptions. Residuals versus Fitted Plot: This compares the residuals’ variance to ensure that they are homoscedastic, or non-linear. The residuals should ideally be distributed randomly along the horizontal line. The residuals in this case appear to follow a pattern that suggests possible heteroscedasticity and non-linearity as the fitted values rise. The Normal Q-Q Plot evaluates the normality of the residual distribution. The lines that follow imply normalcy. Possible deviations from normalcy are indicated by this plot’s deviations from the straight line, particularly at the tails. Spread-Location, also called Scale-Location Plot: This is an additional homoscedasticity check. Heteroscedasticity in the data is suggested by the plot’s widening spread. Leverage vs. Residuals Plot: This finds significant observations that might significantly affect the regression line. It is possible that points outside of the dashed Cook’s distance lines have an impact. There are a few higher leverage points in the plot, but they don’t seem to be outside of Cook’s distance lines, indicating that there aren’t any specific problems with significant outliers.

The most common method for calculating a model’s prediction error for quantitative data is to use the Root Mean Square Error (RMSE). A better fit between the model and the data is indicated by lower RMSE values. Considering the given RMSEs:Of the three models tested, the Multiple Linear Regression model has the lowest RMSE (0.9340931), suggesting that it has the best predictive accuracy for the tested data.

For this specific dataset, the Random Forest Model has the highest RMSE (0.9765617), indicating that it has the lowest predictive accuracy. In terms of predictive accuracy, the Regression Tree model is in the middle with an RMSE (0.9520310) that is marginally higher than that of the Multiple Linear Regression but lower than that of the Random Forest Model.

Deciles (10%, 20%, etc.) on the independent variable is used to rank the dataset according to the values predicted by the model. The mean actual response within each decile is plotted on the independent variable side. The model appears to be most accurate for the top 10% of predictions, based on the tallest bar at the 10th percentile. The model’s predictive power decreases for lower-ranked predictions, as evidenced by the mean response declining across the deciles. In line with the lowest expectations, the smallest bar at the 100th percentile displays the lowest mean response. In conclusion, the model predicts higher responses more accurately than lower ones, which may be helpful for resource allocation or marketing targeting strategies.
